{{Other uses|Biological material (disambiguation)}} {{Refimprove|date=June 2018}}
'''Cellular components''' are the complex [[biomolecule]]s and [[structural biology|structures]] of which [[cell (biology)|cells]], and thus living [[organism]]s, are composed. Cells are the structural and functional units of life. The smallest organisms are single cells, while the largest organisms are assemblages of trillions of cells. DNA is found in nearly all living cells; each cell carries chromosome(s) having a distinctive DNA sequence.
Examples include [[macromolecule]]s such as [[protein]]s and [[nucleic acid]]s, [[biomolecular complex]]es such as a [[ribosome]], and structures such as [[biological membrane|membranes]], and [[organelle]]s. While the majority of cellular components are located within the cell itself, some may exist in [[extracellular]] areas of an organism.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vasyutin|first=I. A.|last2=Lyundup|first2=A. V.|last3=Viranov|first3=A. Z.|last4=Butnaru|first4=D. V.|last5=Kuznetsov|first5=S. L.|date=2017|title=Urethra Reconstruction with Tissue-Engineering Technology|journal=Vestnik Rossiiskoi Akademii Meditsinskikh Nauk|volume=72|issue=1|pages=17–25|issn=0869-6047|pmid=29308838}}</ref>
Cellular components may also be called '''biological matter''' or '''biological material'''. Most biological matter has the characteristics of [[soft matter]], being governed by relatively small energies. All known life is made of biological matter. To be differentiated from other [[hypothetical types of biochemistry|theoretical or fictional life forms]], such life may be called ''[[carbon-based life|carbon-based]]'', ''cellular'', ''organic'', ''biological'', or even simply ''living'' – as some definitions of life exclude [[hypothetical types of biochemistry]].
