{{Infobox company | name = SP Manweb plc | logo = Manweb.png | type = [[Private company|Private]] | slogan = | foundation = 1990 | location = | industry = [[Electricity generation]], [[Electric power transmission|transmission]], [[Electricity distribution|distribution]] | products = [[Electric power|Electricity]] | parent = [[Iberdrola]] | homepage = [http://www.scottishpower.com www.scottishpower.com] }} '''MANWEB''' (Merseyside And North Wales Electricity Board) was the [[regional electricity company|regional electricity]] supplier and distributor for [[Merseyside]], [[North Wales]] and parts of [[Cheshire]]. It is now part of [[SP Energy Networks]], itself a subsidiary of the [[Spain|Spanish]] energy company [[Iberdrola]]. In September 1994, MANWEB announced plans to slash five hundred jobs in the workforce.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/manweb-plans-to-cut-staff-by-500-1447291.html|title=Manweb plans to cut staff by 500|publisher=www.independent.co.uk|date=7 September 1994|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>
It was originally created in 1947 as the nationalised Merseyside and North Wales Electricity Board in the [[Electricity Act 1947 (UK)|Electricity Act 1947]], but was [[privatization|privatised]] in 1990 to become Manweb plc.
It was purchased by [[Scottish Power]] in January 1996, and subsequently become SP Manweb plc. The Manweb name continued to be used alongside the Scottish Power logo on home and retail publications until the middle of 2007, when it was replaced by "ScottishPower".
However, the Merseyside, Cheshire and North Wales electricity distributor continues as SP Manweb plc, which is managed along with the Scottish transmission operators SP Distribution plc and SP Transmission plc as [[Scottish Power#Energy Networks|SP Energy Networks]]. A fourth company, SP Power Systems Ltd maintains the distribution networks for each of these companies.<ref>[http://www.spenergynetworks.co.uk/AboutUs/default.asp Energy Networks: About Us]</ref>
