{{Infobox book <!-- |italic title = (see above) --> | name = The Economical Environmentalist | image = | caption = | author = Prashant Vaze | title_orig = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = [[English language|English]] | series = | subject = | genre = | publisher = | pub_date = | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = | isbn = | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''The Economical Environmentalist''''' is a book by [[Prashant Vaze]] about the effects of climate change and what practical measures can be taken to reduce the amount of energy one consumes.<ref name="FT-Hartford">{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/ed0ebece-ef65-11de-86c4-00144feab49a.html|title=Lights on – or off? Low-carbon living is anything but easy...|date=2 January 2010|accessdate=28 August 2010|publisher=[[Financial Times]]}}</ref> It covers how best to save energy and points out contradictions such as "The one that particularly exasperates me is the “food miles” obsession, whereby we eschew tomatoes from [[Spain]] and roses flown in from [[Kenya]], in favour of local products grown in a heated greenhouse with a far greater carbon footprint."<ref name="FT-Hartford" /> In the book he compares the savings available for several real-world examples of people so one can see what changes are possible to make.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcrn.org.uk/research-library/consumption/sustainability/economical-environmentalist|title=The Economical Environmentalist|publisher=Food Climate Research Network|accessdate=16 June 2013}}</ref>
